## 13. Data Collection, Privacy, and User Rights Notice

BubblesTheDev is committed to protecting user privacy.

The BubblesTheDev Web Browser is designed around local-first handling of browser data, user control, transparency, accessibility-focused improvements, and privacy-focused defaults.

The BubblesTheDev Web Browser does **not** include built-in telemetry, built-in analytics services for ordinary browsing, built-in behavioral advertising profiles, or built-in cloud synchronization by default.

Specifically:

* No telemetry services are embedded in the Software.
* No background analytics services are executed.
* No behavioral tracking mechanisms are included.
* No advertising identifiers are generated or transmitted.
* No cloud-based synchronization features are implemented.
* No automatic diagnostics upload path is enabled for ordinary diagnostics behavior.
* No built-in silent auto-updater service is included.

Normal browser data is intended to remain on the user’s device unless the user chooses to interact with external websites, external search providers, downloads, supported streaming services, privacy-safe diagnostics features, update flows, or other third-party services through normal browser use.

Local browser data may include, where applicable, settings, history, bookmarks, saved-password metadata, encrypted saved-password vault entries, imported extension metadata, imported VPN profile metadata, toolbar visibility, bookmark bar visibility, selected shell theme, per-site permission settings, Streaming Hub session partitions, Music Player settings, Music Downloader state, gaming and streaming performance settings, local AI settings, current-session AI preferences, encrypted profile-isolated AI memory for standard profiles, cached internal search suggestions, install-linked path metadata, and accessibility preferences such as reading, focus, contrast, motion, spacing, and related user-preference options.

The Software may write browser-state data locally and may protect that data with compressed persistence, operating-system-backed protection, credential-backed protection, or other local protection mechanisms where available.

Saved passwords are stored separately from the main browser data file and are intended to be encrypted before being written to disk.

Diagnostics are generated locally. Runtime diagnostic entries may be written to a local diagnostics directory. Privacy-safe diagnostics are intended to remain user-controlled, narrower than general browser data collection, and disabled by default unless the user enables them.

Optional local AI features, if included, are intended to support on-device behavior where available. Standard profiles may keep encrypted AI memory locally, while incognito or other ephemeral contexts are intended to avoid persistent AI memory.

The browser may include accessibility-focused features intended to improve reading comfort, visibility, motion reduction, control size, and continuity across sessions. Accessibility preferences are intended to remain local to the user’s device by default.

The browser may include installer-based update behavior. That update model is intended to use visible update handling, verified HTTPS endpoints, SHA-256 checked installer launches, and installer-time registration support where available rather than a hidden silent updater service.

The browser may still generate normal network traffic when the user opens websites, signs into services, downloads files, uses search features, uses passkeys or WebAuthn, uses update checks, manually sends approved diagnostics, or uses supported online features. Third-party websites and services may process information under their own privacy policies, cookie policies, and terms.

The browser is not designed to make legal, financial, employment, health, housing, insurance, government-benefit, or similarly significant automated decisions about users.

Users may have privacy, transparency, access, correction, deletion, portability, restriction, objection, accessibility, or related legal rights depending on their location and applicable law.

Any future feature that would materially change this privacy posture would be clearly disclosed in updated license, privacy, or release documentation.
